kade","Beta-1 receptor mediated cardiac stimulation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 receptor mediated vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism by which noradrenaline increases blood pressure. When noradrenaline binds to alpha-1 receptors on vascular smooth muscle, it triggers intracellular calcium release leading to vasoconstriction and increased peripheral vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-1 receptor mediated cardiac stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E - noradrenaline has only minor effects at beta adrenergic receptors compared to alpha adrenergic receptors, so this is not a primary mechanism of action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect calcium channel activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Noradrenaline works through receptor-mediated mechanisms, not direct ion channel effects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscarinic receptor activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Muscarinic receptors are activated by acetylcholine, not noradrenaline\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium channel blockade\u003C/strong\u003E - Noradrenaline does not directly affect sodium channels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile noradrenaline has minor beta-1 effects on the heart (increasing contractility and heart rate), its vasoconstrictive effects through alpha-1 receptors are the predominant mechanism for blood pressure elevation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Noradrenaline causes vasoconstriction primarily through activation of alpha-1 adrenergic receptors on vascular smooth muscle.","Noradrenaline increases blood pressure through both vasoconstriction and increased cardiac contractility.","Beta-1 adrenergic receptors mediate the cardiac effects of noradrenaline including increased heart rate and contractility."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16865"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54100"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:00:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:01:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9555"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"